olk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1112–about 1191":"1112–about 1191","1112–1191":"1112–1191","1116–Female":"1116–Deceased","1132–Female":"1132–Deceased","1138–1220":"1138–1220","1141–1198":"1141–1198","–Female":"Deceased","1089–1166":"1089–1166","1094–Female":"1094–Deceased","about 1191":"about 1191","1132":"1132","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1141":"1141","1094":"1094","1191":"1191","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1112":"1112","1166":"1166","1089":"1089","about 1166":"about 1166","England":"England, United Kingdom","West Greenwich, Kent, England":"West Greenwich, Kent, England","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Cokefeld was born in 1112, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam de Cokefeld, was 23 and his mother, Adelicia de Criketot, was 18. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Postalina. He died about 1191, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1112–about 1191":"1112–umbes 1191","1112–1191":"1112–1191","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1138–1220":"1138–1220","1141–1198":"1141–1198","–Female":"Surnud","1089–1166":"1089–1166","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","about 1191":"umbes 1191","1132":"1132","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1141":"1141","1094":"1094","1191":"1191","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1112":"1112","1166":"1166","1089":"1089","about 1166":"umbes 1166","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Greenwich, Kent, England":"West Greenwich, Kent, England","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1112–about 1191":"1112–noin 1191","1112–1191":"1112–1191","1116–Female":"1116–Kuollut","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","1138–1220":"1138–1220","1141–1198":"1141–1198","–Female":"Kuollut","1089–1166":"1089–1166","1094–Female":"1094–Kuollut","about 1191":"noin 1191","1132":"1132","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1141":"1141","1094":"1094","1191":"1191","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1112":"1112","1166":"1166","1089":"1089","about 1166":"noin 1166","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","West Greenwich, Kent, England":"Wes